#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:676
msgid "What can this plugin do and how does it work?"
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:681
msgid ""
"This plugin is privacy-oriented: optimization runs on your server and does not "
"require sending your site data to third-party services."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:683
msgid ""
"WP Optimizer is modular, so you can enable only the features you need to keep the "
"plugin overhead low."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:685
msgid "Server enhancements such as compression, browser caching, and server rules."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:686
msgid "Caching layers for queries, database results, objects, and static pages."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:687
msgid "Minification for HTML, CSS, and JavaScript."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:688
msgid "Local image optimization and conversion workflows."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:689
msgid "Database cleanup, optimization, and backups."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:690
msgid "Security hardening and WordPress behavior toggles."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:691
msgid "Update controls, diagnostics, logs, and admin utilities."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:693
msgid ""
"Because modules can affect different parts of WordPress, the safest approach is to "
"enable one feature at a time and test the front end after each change."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:700
msgid "What should I enable first on a live site?"
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:704
msgid ""
"Start with lower-risk optimizations, then move to the more aggressive ones only "
"after testing."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:706
#, php-format
msgid ""
"Begin with <a href=\"%s\">browser cache and compression settings</a> because they "
"usually improve delivery without changing page logic."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:707
#, php-format
msgid ""
"Configure <a href=\"%s\">media optimization</a> for new uploads before launching "
"large bulk jobs."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:708
#, php-format
msgid ""
"Create a <a href=\"%s\">database backup</a> before cleanup tasks or bigger tuning "
"sessions."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:709
#, php-format
msgid ""
"Add <a href=\"%s\">cache</a> and <a href=\"%s\">minify</a> last, enabling one "
"option at a time and verifying the front end after each step."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:717
msgid "Where can I configure optimization parameters?"
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:721
#, php-format
msgid ""
"Most optimization options are configurable in the <a href=\"%s\">Modules Options "
"panel</a>."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:722
#, php-format
msgid ""
"Global tasks such as cron, module activation, telemetry, reset, export, and restore "
"are available from the <a href=\"%s\">Settings page</a>."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:729
msgid "Can cache or minify break my layout?"
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:733
msgid ""
"Yes. Aggressive caching and front-end minification can expose conflicts in themes "
"or plugins that rely on specific asset order, inline scripts, or dynamic output."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:735
#, php-format
msgid ""
"Enable <a href=\"%s\">minify</a> gradually: HTML, CSS, and JavaScript do not need "
"to be turned on all at once."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:736
#, php-format
msgid ""
"After each change, clear or reset <a href=\"%s\">cache</a> and test important pages "
"while logged out as well."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:737
msgid ""
"If something breaks, disable the last option you enabled first. That is usually the "
"fastest way to isolate the conflict."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:745
msgid "How does the media optimizer work?"
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:749
msgid "Media optimizer works in three different ways:"
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:751
#, php-format
msgid ""
"By a scheduled event it's able to collect and optimize any media uploaded daily. <a "
"href='%s'>Here</a> you can configure all schedule related settings."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:752
msgid ""
"By a specific path scanner, Media optimizer will run a background activity to "
"optimize all images present in the input path."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:753
msgid ""
"By a whole database scanner, Media optimizer will run a background activity to "
"check all images saved in your WordPress library optimizing each image and every "
"thumbnail associated."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:755
#, php-format
msgid ""
"Any image optimization will be run following your settings set <a href=\"%s\">Here</"
"a>."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:762
msgid "Why are image optimization jobs not starting?"
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:766
msgid ""
"Bulk image optimization runs in background, so it depends on the plugin scheduler "
"and on image libraries available on the server."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:768
#, php-format
msgid ""
"Verify that <a href=\"%s\">cron is active</a>; background jobs will not progress if "
"scheduled tasks are not running."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:769
msgid ""
"Check that Imagick or GD is available in PHP. Imagick gives the best coverage, but "
"GD can still handle basic processing."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:770
#, php-format
msgid ""
"Review your <a href=\"%s\">media settings</a> before starting a full-library scan "
"so the job uses the correct quality and format options."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:778
msgid "Do I need Redis or Memcached for object cache?"
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:782
msgid ""
"Only the object cache feature requires Redis or Memcached. The other optimization "
"modules can still be used without them."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:784
#, php-format
msgid ""
"If your server does not provide Redis or Memcached, leave <a href=\"%s\">object "
"cache</a> disabled."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:785
msgid ""
"Static page cache, database/query cache, browser cache, compression, and minify do "
"not depend on an external object cache server."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:793
msgid "How can I clean the database safely?"
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:797
msgid ""
"Database cleanup is most useful when you do it conservatively and with a rollback "
"path ready."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:799
#, php-format
msgid ""
"Create a fresh <a href=\"%s\">database backup</a> before deleting revisions, "
"transients, orphaned data, or other leftovers."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:800
#, php-format
msgid ""
"Run cleanup tasks from the <a href=\"%s\">Database module</a> when the site is "
"stable and no import, migration, or major update is running."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:801
msgid ""
"If the result is not what you expected, restore the backup first instead of "
"guessing which rows changed."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:809
msgid "Can I export settings before major changes?"
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:813
#, php-format
msgid ""
"Yes. The <a href=\"%s\">Settings page</a> lets you export, import, reset, or "
"restore plugin options."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:814
msgid ""
"Use an export before testing aggressive cache, minify, or security changes so you "
"can quickly return to a known-good configuration."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:821
msgid "Does WP Optimizer work on multisite?"
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:825
msgid "Yes. The plugin supports multisite and can be network-activated."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:826
#, php-format
msgid ""
"Even on multisite, test optimization changes gradually from the <a "
"href=\"%s\">module settings</a> because each subsite may use different themes, "
"plugins, and traffic patterns."
msgstr ""

